Here is a clear explanation of why it is structured this way and exactly what steps are needed if you want to enable live webcam video and microphone audio in the Social Lounge:

Why doesn't it work like Zoom or Google Meet right now?
WebRTC establishes peer-to-peer connections:

1-to-1 Calls (Simple): Connection is direct between 2 people. This is lightweight and already works in your app’s direct message section.
Group Calls (Complex): If 5 people join a group call and connect directly to each other, every user's browser must upload their video to 4 different people and download 4 different videos simultaneously.
As more people join, this mesh network quickly overloads the user's internet bandwidth and CPU, causing lag, freezes, and browser crashes.
To solve this, group calling apps (like WhatsApp, Zoom, or Google Meet) upload all video streams to a central cloud media server called an SFU (Selective Forwarding Unit). This server processes the feeds and forwards them to each participant efficiently.

If we want to add live Group Video & Audio, what do we need to do?
Here are the 2 primary ways to implement this:

Option A: Use a Third-Party API (Highly Recommended & Easiest)
Instead of running your own video servers, you can integrate a developer service like Agora.io, LiveKit Cloud, or Daily.co. They handle all the server hosting and scaling.

